Let's say you have two source files: `foo.c` and `bar.cpp`, and you want to link them both to the same library `libmylib.a` which includes both C and C++ code.

To ensure that your C++ code can access the C functions correctly, you will need to use the `extern "C"` declaration in the header file.

For example, in `mylib.h`:

```c
#ifndef MYLIB_H
#define MYLIB_H

#ifdef __cplusplus
extern "C" {
#endif

void my_c_function();

#ifdef __cplusplus
}
#endif

#endif
```

Make sure to wrap the function declarations in `extern "C" { }` only when compiling with a C++ compiler.

Now, in your `foo.c` and `bar.cpp` files, you can include `mylib.h` and call `my_c_function()`:

```c
#include "mylib.h"

int main() {
    my_c_function();
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
#include "mylib.h"

int main() {
    my_c_function();
    return 0;
}
```

When you compile the code, you can use the same library for both C and C++ source files:

```bash
$ gcc -c foo.c
$ g++ -c bar.cpp
$ ar rcs libmylib.a foo.o bar.o
$ gcc -o myprog myprog.c libmylib.a
$ g++ -o myprog myprog.cpp libmylib.a
``` 

This will generate an executable that links both the C and C++ code to the same library.

If the header file of the third-party library uses C++ templates, you cannot use `extern "C"` to include it in your C code. C++ templates use C++ language features and cannot be used in C code.

In this case, you should use a separate compilation unit for the C++ code that uses the library, and link it with your C code:

1. Create a `.cpp` file that includes the header of the third-party library and implements the functions using the C++ templates:

    `cpp_code.cpp`:

    ```cpp
    #include "third_party_library.h"

    template<typename T>
    T add(T a, T b) {
      return a + b
    }

    extern "C" {
      int add_int(int a, int b) {
        return add(a, b);
      }

      double add_double(double a, double b) {
        return add(a, b);
      }
    }
    ```

2. Compile the `.cpp` file into an object file:

    ```bash
    $ g++ -c -o cpp_code.o cpp_code.cpp
    ```

3. Create a header file for the C functions that wrap the C++ templates:

    `cpp_code.h`:

    ```c
    #ifndef CPP_CODE_H
    #define CPP_CODE_H

    #ifdef __cplusplus
    extern "C" {
    #endif

    int add_int(int a, int b);

    double add_double(double a, double b);

    #ifdef __cplusplus
    }
    #endif

    #endif
    ```

4. Include the header file in your C code and call the C functions:

    `main.c`

    ```c
    #include "cpp_code.h"
    #include <stdio.h>

    int main() {
      int a = 1;
      int b = 2;
      int result = add_int(a, b);
      printf("add_int(%d, %d) = %d\n", a, b, result);
      double c = 1.2;
      double d = 3.4;
      double double_result = add_double(c, d);
      printf("add_double(%f, %f) = %f\n", c, d, double_result);

      return 0;
    }
    ```

5. Link your C code with the object file:

    ```bash
    $ gcc -o myprog main.c cpp_code.o
    ```

This approach allows you to use C code to call the C++ templates in the third-party library without using `extern "C"`, and without modifying the third-party library's headers.

If you cannot recompile `libb` and it is only available as a precompiled shared library, you can still use the wrapper library approach.

Here's what you can do:

1. Create the C wrapper library for `liba` as described earlier:

    `wrapper.c`:

    ```c
    #include "liba.h"

    int my_c_function() {
        return c_function();
    }
    ```

    `wrapper.h`:

    ```c
    #ifndef WRAPPER_H
    #define WRAPPER_H

    int my_c_function();

    #endif
    ```

2. Link your C code with the `libb` shared library and the wrapper library for `liba`, using the `-Wl,-rpath` option to specify the location of the precompiled `libb` library:

    ```bash
    $ gcc -o myprog myprog.c -L. -lwrapper -Wl,-rpath=/path/to/libb -lb
    ```

    The `-Wl,-rpath=/path/to/libb` option tells the linker to add `/path/to/libb` to the runtime library search path, so that it can find the `libb` shared library at runtime.

3. Use the wrapper library functions in your code:

    ```c
    #include "wrapper.h"
    #include <stdio.h>

    int main() {
        int result = my_c_function();
        printf("result = %d\n", result);
        return 0;
    }
    ```

This approach allows you to use your C code to call the C functions in `liba` using `wrapper.h`, and call the C++ functions in `libb` using its own API, without modifying any of the libraries' headers or source code.

If you get an undefined symbol error for a C++ name mangled symbol in `libb` at runtime, it means that `libb` is trying to link directly to the C++ functions in `liba`, which are not accessible from your C code.

To avoid this issue, you need to use the wrapper library for `liba` when linking `libb`, so that it uses the functions in the wrapper library instead of the C++ functions in `liba`.

Here's what you can do:

1. Create the C wrapper library for `liba` as described earlier:

    `wrapper.c`:

    ```c
    #include "liba.h"

    int my_c_function() {
        return c_function();
    }
    ```

    `wrapper.h`:

    ```c
    #ifndef WRAPPER_H
    #define WRAPPER_H

    int my_c_function();

    #endif
    ```

2. Link your C code with `libb`, the wrapper library for `liba`, and the C++ standard library, using `-Wl,-rpath` to specify the location of `libb` and `-Wl,-E` to export symbols from the wrapper library:

    ```bash
    $ gcc -o myprog myprog.c -L. -Wl,-rpath=/path/to/libb -Wl,-E -lwrapper -lb -lstdc++
    ```

    The `-Wl,-E` option tells the linker to export symbols from the wrapper library, so that `libb` can link to them.

3. Use the wrapper library functions in `libb` by including `wrapper.h` and calling them directly, instead of calling the C functions in `liba`:

    `libb.cpp`:

    ```cpp
    #include "wrapper.h"

    int cpp_function() {
        int a = 1;
        int b = 2;
        int result = my_c_function() + a + b;
        return result;
    }
    ```

This approach allows you to use your C code to call the C functions in `liba` using `wrapper.h`, and call the C++ functions in `libb` using the wrapper library, so that all functions use C linkage and share the same API.

You're right, my apologies for the confusion. If `libb` has C++ linkage to functions in `liba`, and you have no control over the source code of either library to change their linkage, you may need to use a C++ program to call the functions in `libb`.

Here's what you can do:

1. Create a C++ program that includes the headers for both `liba` and `libb`, and calls the C++ functions in `libb`:

    `main.cpp`:

    ```cpp
    #include <iostream>
    #include "liba.h"
    #include "libb.h"

    int main() {
        int a = 1;
        int b = 2;
        int result = cpp_function(a, b);
        std::cout << "result = " << result << std::endl;
        return 0;
    }
    ```

2. Compile the `main.cpp` file and link it with both `liba` and `libb` using a C++ compiler:

    ```bash
    $ g++ -o myprog main.cpp -L/path/to/liba -L/path/to/libb -la -lb
    ```

    Note that you need to use a C++ compiler to link the program, as it includes C++ code from `libb`.

    You may also need to specify the path to the `liba` and `libb` libraries using the `-L` option.

3. Run the program:

    ```bash
    $ ./myprog
    ```

This approach allows you to use both `liba` and `libb` in a C++ program without modifying their headers or source code, and without affecting your existing C code.
